1
00:00:00,605 --> 00:00:20,182
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:20,163 --> 00:00:35,521
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:40,631 --> 00:00:50,625
I thought we'd talk a little bit tonight about those qualities that we can develop in daily life.

4
00:00:52,667 --> 00:00:58,274
Just a little bit of reading I've done over these past couple of weeks.

5
00:00:58,334 --> 00:01:00,896
I've come across this word, dignity.

6
00:01:02,840 --> 00:01:04,242
I hadn't really thought about dignity.

7
00:01:05,924 --> 00:01:06,944
I thought, dignity.

8
00:01:07,064 --> 00:01:07,686
Dignity.

9
00:01:15,242 --> 00:01:17,546
It's not a common or garden word, is it?

10
00:01:17,986 --> 00:01:19,930
Dignity.

11
00:01:20,069 --> 00:01:22,554
We sort of associate it really with emperors, don't we?

12
00:01:22,733 --> 00:01:24,215
Royalty, aristocracy.

13
00:01:25,977 --> 00:01:27,680
They act in a dignified way.

14
00:01:28,903 --> 00:01:29,222
Don't they?

15
00:01:31,525 --> 00:01:32,707
In the past they did.

16
00:01:32,727 --> 00:01:33,950
In the past they did.

17
00:01:33,969 --> 00:01:38,195
Well, I think they did.

18
00:01:41,871 --> 00:01:44,594
And unfortunately, it sort of moves towards snobbery.

19
00:01:44,736 --> 00:01:49,361
So that's not the best of examples, really.

20
00:01:49,621 --> 00:01:52,105
But we do talk about dignified behavior, don't we?

21
00:01:52,125 --> 00:01:53,947
You'll hear it, say, people at funerals.

22
00:01:54,328 --> 00:01:56,730
You know, somebody who's been heavily grieved.

23
00:01:57,090 --> 00:01:58,793
They behave in a dignified way.

24
00:01:59,813 --> 00:02:09,887
People under duress or in court falsely accused or even properly accused sort of act in a dignified manner.

25
00:02:12,550 --> 00:02:37,056
sort of a certain bearing isn't it but that bearing is um it's out of a certain qualities that we have in us isn't it um i i don't know how many of you saw the i think it's a youtube wasn't it of of saddam hussein's execution anybody see that no i did

26
00:02:39,634 --> 00:02:45,662
Later on I'm going to talk about what we shouldn't be putting in our minds.

27
00:02:48,686 --> 00:02:52,349
And you have to say he was surrounded by jackals.

28
00:02:53,831 --> 00:02:54,893
Jackals, it was awful.

29
00:02:56,955 --> 00:02:57,997
Just the cruelty of it.

30
00:02:58,197 --> 00:03:01,921
I mean the one or two were trying to give him instructions on what was going to happen.

31
00:03:02,682 --> 00:03:04,183
But the rest were taunting him.

32
00:03:05,966 --> 00:03:08,949
And within all that he seemed to maintain...

33
00:03:09,469 --> 00:03:12,693
Well, you know, you could talk about a dignified bearing.

34
00:03:15,015 --> 00:03:15,856
Or maintained.

35
00:03:15,877 --> 00:03:22,163
You must, I mean, that sort of, perhaps that cool stillness that comes when you know you're going to die.

36
00:03:22,585 --> 00:03:28,031
I don't know, but I was quite amazed by that.

37
00:03:28,050 --> 00:03:36,000
And his daughter then wrote or spoke saying that she was proud of her father in the way that he faced his death, you know.

38
00:03:39,811 --> 00:03:42,093
Charles I, Charles I, isn't it?

39
00:03:42,114 --> 00:03:43,256
Yeah, he got his head chopped off.

40
00:03:43,717 --> 00:03:46,721
So he was, he had a certain dignity.

41
00:03:51,728 --> 00:03:52,770
And then he lost his head.

42
00:03:52,789 --> 00:03:53,610
And then he lost his head.

43
00:03:55,454 --> 00:04:04,586
But, the sort of inner, an inner strength comes up when we're in,

44
00:04:04,853 --> 00:04:12,842
when we're under duress, doesn't it, we find an inner strength, which sort of, we maintain a dignified posture.

45
00:04:13,984 --> 00:04:27,199
In a more, it comes out in a body language, in a more scriptural incident, when Bimbisara, who was the king of Magadha, that was the kingdom that was really growing in those days, around Varanasi, on the Ganges,

46
00:04:28,107 --> 00:04:36,617
When he saw the Buddha doing arms round, it seems he was taken by his bearing, by the dignified way he was doing it.

47
00:04:37,398 --> 00:04:43,384
And it struck him to such an extent that he actually wanted to know who that monk was.

48
00:04:44,045 --> 00:04:46,067
And that's how the friendship was first formed.

49
00:04:53,336 --> 00:04:55,278
Siddhu is self-worth, isn't it?

50
00:04:56,827 --> 00:05:01,593
feel worthy of yourself, to feel, to have a sort of dignified bearing.

51
00:05:05,797 --> 00:05:07,437
I mean, that can slip into pride.

52
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:15,146
But there must be some sort of self-worthiness, I think, in the word dignity.

53
00:05:17,168 --> 00:05:18,608
Because we feel good about yourself.

54
00:05:21,572 --> 00:05:22,632
I think...

55
00:05:25,262 --> 00:05:34,572
I think that's a deeper goodness that we feel about ourselves if we see our lives in terms of a spiritual life, in terms of spiritual growth.

56
00:05:36,415 --> 00:05:38,697
Puts it into a much greater context, doesn't it?

57
00:05:40,959 --> 00:05:55,134
I mean, if one has a bearing because of status that's put upon one, that society puts upon you, certain kudos, having a job and all that, then that bearing, that dignity that comes with it

58
00:05:55,975 --> 00:06:00,218
in any job really, is dependent on the job.

59
00:06:01,560 --> 00:06:13,213
But if our sense of worthiness comes from living a spiritual life, then really nothing that happens on the outside can upset that feeling of self-worthiness.

60
00:06:18,358 --> 00:06:22,201
That's a theory.

61
00:06:24,932 --> 00:06:36,083
I mean, this life, in terms of any, all these religions, this life is seen as a training ground, isn't it?

62
00:06:36,103 --> 00:06:36,884
Training ground.

63
00:06:40,146 --> 00:06:45,232
It's not a matter of being perfect in order to have dignity.

64
00:06:45,252 --> 00:06:47,074
It's not a matter of having arrived.

65
00:06:48,134 --> 00:06:53,639
It's the sense of worthiness you get from treading a worthwhile path in life.

66
00:06:56,589 --> 00:07:05,699
And I came across these ten factors, these ten qualities of a king in the scriptures.

67
00:07:08,442 --> 00:07:10,384
I think they're commentarial.

68
00:07:10,403 --> 00:07:15,548
They come in the Jātaka, the tales of the Buddha's past lives.

69
00:07:17,290 --> 00:07:19,793
But they give us something to sort of work around.

70
00:07:20,994 --> 00:07:26,579
And the one that seems to always head the list is generosity, charity.

71
00:07:29,428 --> 00:07:41,213
It's interesting that when he was attacked by the great doubt just before he became awakened, and it's put mythologically as Mara attacked him.

72
00:07:43,817 --> 00:07:45,261
The great doubt was...

73
00:07:46,422 --> 00:07:47,302
Who was he?

74
00:07:47,343 --> 00:07:52,226
I mean, who was he amongst all human beings to think that would be an end to suffering?

75
00:07:52,247 --> 00:07:56,971
Who was he to have that presumption that he could find the end of suffering?

76
00:07:57,331 --> 00:07:59,314
It was a real deep self-doubt.

77
00:08:01,415 --> 00:08:14,168
And he touches the earth, you see, and the goddess arises to say that the quality that he's perfected

78
00:08:14,704 --> 00:08:22,476
which allows him to have this presumption, inverted commas, is the perfection of generosity.

79
00:08:24,860 --> 00:08:26,684
Which means that he's not doing it just for himself.

80
00:08:28,266 --> 00:08:29,208
Not doing it just for himself.

81
00:08:29,247 --> 00:08:38,383
He sees himself already connected to the whole of humanity, the whole mass of suffering.

82
00:08:39,105 --> 00:08:47,188
And that's what gives him his sense of self-worth back, to go back into the meditation.

83
00:08:47,389 --> 00:08:50,118
And after that, he makes the break.

84
00:08:51,341 --> 00:08:51,883
It's very interesting.

85
00:08:59,996 --> 00:09:08,466
That's a quality of not getting flustered, not getting angry when we lose something or when somebody takes something.

86
00:09:09,368 --> 00:09:20,080
You know, there's the Zen story of the monk who was sitting there and a thief came and took all his possessions, even his clothes, left him naked in the moonlight.

87
00:09:20,100 --> 00:09:26,326
And he looked up at the moon and he said, if only I could have, this beautiful moon, if only I could have given him the moon.

88
00:09:26,927 --> 00:09:28,249
See, that's generosity, isn't it?

89
00:09:31,957 --> 00:09:40,870
And it's that spirit of not just giving when you're asked, but letting go of actually giving when you don't feel you want to give.

90
00:09:43,053 --> 00:09:46,578
And to do that, there has to be that connection, doesn't it, to the other.

91
00:09:56,975 --> 00:09:58,557
Generosity

92
00:10:00,325 --> 00:10:05,289
The more generous we are, the more it mirrors back to us our lack of possessiveness.

93
00:10:09,433 --> 00:10:17,883
And when we're generous, we let go of something that we could have used for ourselves, either our wealth or our time for ourselves.

94
00:10:20,206 --> 00:10:22,148
Just to do that is to let go of the self.

95
00:10:22,168 --> 00:10:27,413
I mean, that's the practice of undermining the self-view in action.

96
00:10:28,674 --> 00:10:38,289
This business of undermining self isn't just an act of insight, like when we observe things as separate and all that.

97
00:10:39,611 --> 00:10:42,557
It manifests in our virtues.

98
00:10:45,981 --> 00:10:49,047
And generosity, the Buddha puts it always at the head of the list.

99
00:10:50,461 --> 00:11:19,557
because the more generous we are the more we have to renounce and that process of renunciation is the spiritual path it doesn't mean to say that you have to actually let go of everything but you have to have that attitude with everything of being able to let go of it should occasion demand develop that attitude

100
00:11:21,899 --> 00:11:25,384
Sometimes you can play little mental games with that.

101
00:11:27,046 --> 00:11:32,052
Take the most treasured thing you have and then think about it being stolen, being lost.

102
00:11:32,273 --> 00:11:35,317
Would it be that important?

103
00:11:36,678 --> 00:11:36,859
Yes.

104
00:11:41,504 --> 00:11:43,086
Can you let go of something treasured?

105
00:11:43,727 --> 00:11:45,831
Just do a mental game with it.

106
00:11:46,317 --> 00:11:48,538
Because often our fears are unfounded.

107
00:11:48,940 --> 00:11:54,304
We think that if we lose this or lose our jobs or lose that, the world crashes around us.

108
00:11:54,846 --> 00:12:08,200
But if you just turn it into a little story within the mind, using the creativity of the mind to set up a certain situation, a thought experiment, then you see there's nothing.

109
00:12:08,419 --> 00:12:12,183
Even to the point of losing your life, you can try that one.

110
00:12:13,445 --> 00:12:14,046
It's a bit heavy.

111
00:12:16,220 --> 00:12:26,773
Last year I went to Auschwitz and just heroic stories around all those years of that camp.

112
00:12:28,434 --> 00:12:42,413
Auschwitz and just heroic tales of people who act out of kindness and get severely punished or killed.

113
00:12:43,303 --> 00:12:44,004
Killed from it.

114
00:12:44,024 --> 00:12:48,893
And you go there and when you sort of go to the place, it sort of grounds all the stories that you've read.

115
00:12:50,975 --> 00:12:53,120
And it has quite an effect on you.

116
00:12:54,282 --> 00:12:59,529
I think anyway.

117
00:12:59,549 --> 00:13:04,437
So even to the point of being able to let go of our lives, that's the ultimate generous act, isn't it?

118
00:13:05,278 --> 00:13:06,881
Our greater gift as man and all that.

119
00:13:08,498 --> 00:13:10,601
So this generosity digs deep.

120
00:13:11,062 --> 00:13:18,355
It's a profound virtue, isn't it?

121
00:13:18,375 --> 00:13:18,595
Generosity.

122
00:13:18,615 --> 00:13:21,220
Then the next one is morality.

123
00:13:23,283 --> 00:13:27,470
Here we can take it more in the sense of not doing what is wrong.

124
00:13:29,474 --> 00:13:31,317
That's keeping the basic precepts.

125
00:13:36,494 --> 00:13:39,998
Often just to resist the old temptations.

126
00:13:40,958 --> 00:13:44,043
Most of us have given up killing and thieving.

127
00:13:45,544 --> 00:13:48,427
We're not talking about gross sort of behavior.

128
00:13:49,830 --> 00:13:54,034
But just those little things, little greeds, little aversions.

129
00:13:57,198 --> 00:14:03,986
And just to work with them, just to see them as ways of developing that strength of resisting temptations.

130
00:14:05,687 --> 00:14:34,462
even at the more these more subtle levels where we can't talk about good and evil we're talking about unwholesomeness we're talking about unskillful behaviour you know just attachments to a certain routine in our lives or the morning cup of tea that's difficult and just to sort of play little games with ourselves you know like what happens if I don't have my Lapsang Suchong this morning

131
00:14:36,873 --> 00:14:38,654
go through the hell of letting go.

132
00:14:41,236 --> 00:14:49,485
And what that does is it builds up your will, your will to resist what is unwholesome for us.

133
00:14:51,466 --> 00:15:01,277
And the idea is, of course, that you keep doing it until you've lost a real connection with it.

134
00:15:01,557 --> 00:15:06,542
And then when you go back into it to... Is that a door, is it?

135
00:15:06,995 --> 00:15:12,764
There we are.

136
00:15:12,784 --> 00:15:13,866
The cats have come.

137
00:15:13,886 --> 00:15:14,447
What to do?

138
00:15:17,452 --> 00:15:18,293
The cats have arrived.

139
00:15:20,258 --> 00:15:23,482
Fancy.

140
00:15:27,188 --> 00:15:31,736
So you're trying to go back into the routine, see how it is?

141
00:15:32,914 --> 00:15:35,899
Well, it's a case of breaking routine, you know.

142
00:15:35,918 --> 00:15:39,744
The practice is really getting rid of habits and getting other habits.

143
00:15:39,823 --> 00:15:42,388
But as soon as we get a habit, we tend to hold on to it.

144
00:15:43,048 --> 00:15:48,876
Even meditation becomes a sort of obsessive, can become an obsessive thing.

145
00:15:48,897 --> 00:15:52,662
You know, you think your day will collapse if you don't do your 40 minutes.

146
00:15:54,328 --> 00:15:59,499
It's a case of tempting, tempting oneself to let go of things that we've become attached to.

147
00:16:00,341 --> 00:16:09,198
And it strengthens our character, strengthens the will, you see, the ability to resist temptations.

148
00:16:10,140 --> 00:16:13,283
It's not necessarily anything which is negative.

149
00:16:13,303 --> 00:16:15,385
You were talking about the morning cup of tea.

150
00:16:15,405 --> 00:16:18,129
There's actually nothing wrong with the morning cup of tea.

151
00:16:18,849 --> 00:16:20,650
No, that's what I mean.

152
00:16:20,671 --> 00:16:22,552
It's a question of breaking the habit because you become attached to that particular behavior.

153
00:16:23,033 --> 00:16:24,014
Yeah, yeah.

154
00:16:24,033 --> 00:16:32,001
Because the self comforts itself in little ways.

155
00:16:32,022 --> 00:16:34,203
In Christian literature they're called imperfections.

156
00:16:37,226 --> 00:16:37,988
Imperfections.

157
00:16:42,506 --> 00:16:46,572
But the purpose of that is again to renounce.

158
00:16:47,214 --> 00:16:51,802
And in so doing, you create a certain inner strength.

159
00:16:52,081 --> 00:16:52,722
This is the point.

160
00:16:52,903 --> 00:17:02,258
And I think that's one of these things about when you see somebody who has dignity, to use that word, sort of an inner strength.

161
00:17:02,317 --> 00:17:08,126
And it comes from being able to resist what is harmful.

162
00:17:14,619 --> 00:17:17,022
On the positive side, the next one is altruism.

163
00:17:18,625 --> 00:17:26,536
If you remember that verse from the Dhammapada, cease from evil, do good, purify the heart, this is the path, this is the ancient path.

164
00:17:26,556 --> 00:17:31,862
This is the path before the Buddha, this is an ancient path.

165
00:17:33,765 --> 00:17:39,952
Altruism, putting somebody else before yourself, or at least equal to yourself,

166
00:17:40,894 --> 00:17:49,803
When the situation calls for it, you're not saying that there isn't a situation where you're not caring for yourself.

167
00:17:49,943 --> 00:17:50,924
The Buddha is clear about that.

168
00:17:51,525 --> 00:17:54,347
We do things for ourselves, for others, both for ourselves and others.

169
00:17:55,308 --> 00:17:59,893
But this altruism is really an expression of that interconnectedness, isn't it?

170
00:18:00,334 --> 00:18:04,497
Interdependency, sort of recognizing that.

171
00:18:04,517 --> 00:18:09,281
So when we offer our service, we offer our wealth,

172
00:18:11,371 --> 00:18:12,833
put ourselves out for somebody.

173
00:18:15,357 --> 00:18:28,640
There's a lovely passage, the scripture I think is called the Anuruddhas, but there's three Arahats, three fully enlightened monks living together and they live, hopefully not surprisingly, peacefully.

174
00:18:30,163 --> 00:18:33,387
And the Buddha asks Anuruddha, how is it you live peacefully?

175
00:18:34,769 --> 00:18:35,791
And he says, well,

176
00:18:37,662 --> 00:18:44,886
When I get up in the morning, I say to myself, what if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

177
00:18:47,695 --> 00:18:50,305
I think that only works if the others are saying the same thing.

178
00:18:52,511 --> 00:18:54,554
If they're not, I think you'll be messed about.

179
00:18:54,594 --> 00:19:00,601
But at least that attitude, you see, just putting aside what I want to do and let's see what the others want to do.

180
00:19:01,340 --> 00:19:03,523
You're not getting rid of what you want.

181
00:19:03,544 --> 00:19:13,835
You're just putting it aside for a moment so that you can hear what other people want to do, which is not our normal position.

182
00:19:13,875 --> 00:19:16,798
We prefer that other people know what we want to do.

183
00:19:17,352 --> 00:19:18,192
And then we bargain.

184
00:19:19,513 --> 00:19:20,655
Then we have to negotiate.

185
00:19:21,336 --> 00:19:24,339
It's coming around it from the other way and hopefully people respond.

186
00:19:25,381 --> 00:19:26,541
That's sort of altruism.

187
00:19:33,569 --> 00:19:34,191
Honesty.

188
00:19:34,250 --> 00:19:38,935
I think honesty is a great part of this bearing, dignified bearing.

189
00:19:38,955 --> 00:19:39,596
Honesty.

190
00:19:41,128 --> 00:19:48,038
truthfulness with ourselves, truthfulness with others, not to trick people, not to exaggerate.

191
00:19:49,340 --> 00:19:55,709
I mean, that comes close to humility, really, in its proper sense of knowing who we are.

192
00:19:56,190 --> 00:20:02,519
It comes in all sorts of ways, honestly.

193
00:20:03,200 --> 00:20:08,267
Sort of to do one's due at work, to give of one's best at work.

194
00:20:13,157 --> 00:20:13,858
in business.

195
00:20:14,840 --> 00:20:21,752
See, it's funny, on a retreat there was somebody, he was into buying and selling.

196
00:20:23,395 --> 00:20:32,231
And he says he can go to a house and somebody will show him something who hasn't seen the antiques, a road show.

197
00:20:32,251 --> 00:20:36,499
And he'll sort of get out of them that they don't really know it's worth.

198
00:20:37,036 --> 00:20:39,680
So now he can really say, well, look, I'll give you 20 quid for that.

199
00:20:39,980 --> 00:20:42,884
You know, I'll take it off your hands for 20 quid.

200
00:20:42,903 --> 00:20:45,607
And he always sells it for a couple of thousand.

201
00:20:45,627 --> 00:20:48,992
And I could see he was confused because this was business.

202
00:20:49,432 --> 00:20:50,694
This is what you did in business.

203
00:20:51,576 --> 00:20:54,359
But there was some doubt in his mind because he asked, you see.

204
00:20:54,980 --> 00:20:56,343
I mean, what about that, you see.

205
00:20:57,525 --> 00:21:02,731
And before I could say something, you know, I just let it rest in the air, just what the others say.

206
00:21:03,333 --> 00:21:04,775
And there was another businessman there, you see.

207
00:21:04,994 --> 00:21:06,958
And of course, he went on about integrity.

208
00:21:08,643 --> 00:21:10,424
It's like they blew that one out of the water, really.

209
00:21:12,827 --> 00:21:20,196
But it's funny how you can confuse yourself, you know, by having different aims.

210
00:21:20,416 --> 00:21:22,980
So this person's aim, of course, was to make money.

211
00:21:25,202 --> 00:21:28,547
It's not his fault the other person didn't know it was worth.

212
00:21:28,567 --> 00:21:29,327
They should have known better.

213
00:21:29,347 --> 00:21:32,231
It's not his problem, is it?

214
00:21:32,251 --> 00:21:35,915
So that sense of integrity, I think, is part of

215
00:21:38,967 --> 00:22:02,680
part of the quality of dignity to use that word there's 10 of them the other one is kindness kindness

216
00:22:04,144 --> 00:22:04,746
Gentleness.

217
00:22:04,766 --> 00:22:08,951
We often translate metta as loving kindness, don't we?

218
00:22:08,971 --> 00:22:09,653
Kindness.

219
00:22:09,772 --> 00:22:11,476
The quality of being kind.

220
00:22:13,178 --> 00:22:13,920
Being gentle.

221
00:22:15,442 --> 00:22:16,824
It's a lovely word, isn't it?

222
00:22:16,844 --> 00:22:17,345
Kind.

223
00:22:18,125 --> 00:22:20,670
In a sense, the word itself tells us what it is.

224
00:22:21,371 --> 00:22:21,991
Kindness.

225
00:22:24,055 --> 00:22:25,656
I was always amused by gentleman.

226
00:22:26,337 --> 00:22:29,782
I mean, I know in old literature they say gentle woman, but it's very rarely used.

227
00:22:29,863 --> 00:22:30,944
It's the man who's about to be gentle.

228
00:22:34,097 --> 00:22:35,259
A gentleman.

229
00:22:35,279 --> 00:22:35,980
Interesting, eh?

230
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:36,421
Gentle.

231
00:22:38,284 --> 00:22:39,464
Kindness, yeah.

232
00:22:41,667 --> 00:22:43,851
Often it's to see the fragility in others, isn't it?

233
00:22:45,133 --> 00:22:52,142
You know, to see their to see their weaker part and not to take advantage of that or hammer them for it.

234
00:22:57,608 --> 00:23:03,717
Often you can get you can ask people to do things which they wouldn't do if it weren't asked with kindness.

235
00:23:04,490 --> 00:23:08,861
a gentleness about the way we speak to people.

236
00:23:12,891 --> 00:23:15,678
It even extends to obvious.

237
00:23:17,442 --> 00:23:18,786
How did you close the fridge door?

238
00:23:21,887 --> 00:23:44,132
It's just treating everything with that sort of, when I used to go up to the Zen monastery in Throttle Hole, just here in Wexham, North England anyway, they used to insist that we treat even these sort of cracked bits of pottery as if they were Ming vases, you know.

239
00:23:45,242 --> 00:23:49,250
Everything had to be treated with that sort of, you know, very gracious kindness.

240
00:23:50,093 --> 00:23:52,557
And you bow to everything out of gratitude.

241
00:23:52,596 --> 00:23:55,343
You know, bow to the room, bow to the door, doorknob.

242
00:23:55,884 --> 00:24:01,494
And at first it's all game and then you're like, no, no, this is what it's about really.

243
00:24:03,157 --> 00:24:03,699
Kindness.

244
00:24:05,182 --> 00:24:07,707
Remember, these are the qualities that are supposed to be of a king.

245
00:24:11,752 --> 00:24:16,298
Self-control, self-discipline.

246
00:24:16,338 --> 00:24:18,221
It's not a word we particularly like, discipline.

247
00:24:18,862 --> 00:24:24,568
It reminds us of Victoriana and the old ways.

248
00:24:25,810 --> 00:24:38,487
But the interesting thing is that the word discipline actually comes from the word to learn, a disciple, following the advice of a teacher.

249
00:24:46,364 --> 00:24:49,929
On this course, for instance, the schedule was your discipline.

250
00:24:50,490 --> 00:24:52,192
It set out the rotor of the day.

251
00:24:53,073 --> 00:25:01,124
So one tries to follow that particular rotor as best as you can, no matter how you feel or don't feel.

252
00:25:02,346 --> 00:25:04,910
So this discipline is coming from some other center.

253
00:25:05,009 --> 00:25:07,093
It's not coming from feelings.

254
00:25:07,532 --> 00:25:12,539
It's not coming from whether you want to do it or not in that sort of feeling way, whether you're bored or not.

255
00:25:14,038 --> 00:25:23,808
So one has the discipline, the inner strength, the control to actually do what you've set yourself, like resolution.

256
00:25:30,696 --> 00:25:33,720
There was a robbery in Bishop's Castle just down the road.

257
00:25:34,019 --> 00:25:35,781
It's a close town to us.

258
00:25:35,801 --> 00:25:39,726
And I was in the builder's merchant's yacht.

259
00:25:41,596 --> 00:25:45,660
And they said there'd been a robbery in Bishop's Castle.

260
00:25:46,480 --> 00:25:46,961
I said, oh.

261
00:25:48,362 --> 00:25:49,042
I said, why?

262
00:25:49,083 --> 00:25:50,023
I don't know why I said why.

263
00:25:52,425 --> 00:25:55,548
It's not a silly question, really.

264
00:25:55,608 --> 00:25:57,931
It's like the bank robber who was asked, why does he rob the banks?

265
00:25:57,990 --> 00:26:00,032
He said, because that's where the money is.

266
00:26:04,017 --> 00:26:08,160
And he answered me, he said, just lack of discipline, he said, and walked off.

267
00:26:08,721 --> 00:26:09,882
Lack of discipline.

268
00:26:11,126 --> 00:26:15,092
And that's the way he saw it, lack of discipline.

269
00:26:16,272 --> 00:26:23,161
All this bad behavior is all lack of discipline.

270
00:26:26,204 --> 00:26:29,028
I think you have to be careful that it doesn't become a disciplinarian.

271
00:26:29,208 --> 00:26:31,490
I mean, that's where we associate discipline with.

272
00:26:32,332 --> 00:26:33,192
It's more cajoling.

273
00:26:33,232 --> 00:26:39,800
It's more returning to that kindness, to that self-cajoling, to actually do what we'd set ourselves to do.

274
00:26:42,176 --> 00:26:48,648
And when it comes to self-control of the senses, the Buddha's hot on that.

275
00:26:48,669 --> 00:26:51,854
Because everything that comes into the senses is conditioning you.

276
00:26:52,174 --> 00:26:55,300
An act of attention is an act of intention.

277
00:26:55,721 --> 00:26:57,505
Intention is an act of will.

278
00:26:58,906 --> 00:27:04,336
I always like to refer to that example of these billboards on roads.

279
00:27:05,583 --> 00:27:18,922
in the 80s, I was living in Birmingham, and there was obviously some doubt about the efficacy of these billboards, whether they had any worth in terms of advertising.

280
00:27:19,643 --> 00:27:27,294
So the owners of the billboards advertised this really funny perfume from Australia.

281
00:27:28,375 --> 00:27:29,778
I had a funny name, which I've forgotten.

282
00:27:29,837 --> 00:27:30,679
Did you ever see it?

283
00:27:31,367 --> 00:27:38,919
And it had a hat on top of the bottle with corks.

284
00:27:38,939 --> 00:27:39,559
It was really funny.

285
00:27:40,501 --> 00:27:48,753
And the amount of inquiries about this proved without a shadow of a doubt that these billboards worked.

286
00:27:50,977 --> 00:27:54,362
I can't remember the name, but I definitely remember the shape of the product.

287
00:27:54,383 --> 00:27:55,384
Anyway, it didn't exist.

288
00:27:59,144 --> 00:28:04,209
And so there you are on the bus, you see, and you're just lazily looking out and you're catching these bubbles.

289
00:28:04,630 --> 00:28:05,931
And it's coming in, it's coming in.

290
00:28:08,713 --> 00:28:12,597
So the Buddha always talks about restraint of the sense spaces.

291
00:28:13,117 --> 00:28:17,923
Restraint of the sense spaces.

292
00:28:17,942 --> 00:28:21,646
So we have to be careful about what we put into our heads.

293
00:28:22,428 --> 00:28:25,911
What we see on TV, stuff we read.

294
00:28:31,290 --> 00:28:43,932
It's not a matter of guarding ourselves against, shall we say, bad news, but it's just being, you know, just recognizing that what we put into the mind has a conditioning effect, that's all.

295
00:28:44,503 --> 00:28:46,866
Now remember that these conditionings are not everlasting.

296
00:28:47,508 --> 00:28:51,633
It's not as though, oh my God, I'm about to go to the Avicii Hell or something.

297
00:28:52,334 --> 00:29:05,892
It's a case of recognizing that, you know, if there is a negative conditioning in the mind, then we're going to have to suffer, stay with, be patient with that conditioning coming out and exhausting itself.

298
00:29:06,834 --> 00:29:07,153
That's all.

299
00:29:07,855 --> 00:29:11,759
But once we put a conditioning in the mind to which we're attracted,

300
00:29:12,414 --> 00:29:16,862
then there'll always be that, every time you put it in, you're reinforcing that conditioning.

301
00:29:17,002 --> 00:29:17,703
That's the problem.

302
00:29:19,046 --> 00:29:26,157
So it becomes more and more difficult not to resist, more and more difficult to resist the actual temptation.

303
00:29:28,701 --> 00:29:38,557
So this self-control is absolutely necessary for the spiritual life.

304
00:29:39,667 --> 00:29:51,138
See, the Buddha, all these rules that we have, it's 227 on the last count, so many of them were to restrain the monastics from doing things.

305
00:29:51,179 --> 00:29:52,840
I mean, one of them was food.

306
00:29:54,602 --> 00:30:02,269
In the early times, the monks and nuns could go out anytime with their bowl, collect a bit of food, go back, have a munch.

307
00:30:03,230 --> 00:30:05,833
There was no rule as such.

308
00:30:05,853 --> 00:30:07,734
And then the lay people started to complain.

309
00:30:08,271 --> 00:30:10,433
They said, look, your monks are turning up any time of the day.

310
00:30:12,957 --> 00:30:14,778
And they're all rushing off with all this food, you see.

311
00:30:15,640 --> 00:30:16,601
So then he made this rule.

312
00:30:16,701 --> 00:30:23,367
He said, from now on, you have to go out in the morning and you can only go out once and you have to eat it by midday.

313
00:30:24,509 --> 00:30:25,310
And the monks didn't like that.

314
00:30:25,451 --> 00:30:25,971
They rebelled.

315
00:30:26,010 --> 00:30:29,315
They said, no, we're not having that.

316
00:30:29,335 --> 00:30:33,358
But eventually they sort of came to their senses and agreed to have it.

317
00:30:33,378 --> 00:30:36,742
And there were proper arguments like, well, everybody cooks the best food in the evening.

318
00:30:36,824 --> 00:30:38,326
You go in the morning, are you going to get his rice?

319
00:30:40,089 --> 00:30:40,691
But he wouldn't have it.

320
00:30:43,737 --> 00:30:49,007
I can't forgive him.

321
00:30:49,027 --> 00:30:49,928
And you get things like that.

322
00:30:50,328 --> 00:30:56,840
There was once he saw monks coming away from a village or something with loads and loads of cloth.

323
00:30:57,039 --> 00:30:58,801
So he thought, well, that's not right, the robes.

324
00:30:59,542 --> 00:31:08,411
Because by that time, obviously, they'd become well-established in society and were getting lots of presents from there, lots of gifts from lay people.

325
00:31:08,431 --> 00:31:11,994
So he himself went out and seemingly tried to eat.

326
00:31:13,195 --> 00:31:18,141
At night, he just put his, he had his two robes.

327
00:31:19,423 --> 00:31:23,807
And then as the night got a bit cool, he put another robe on top of it.

328
00:31:24,428 --> 00:31:27,490
And in the early morning, the coldest hour, you need another robe.

329
00:31:28,751 --> 00:31:29,373
So he made a rule.

330
00:31:29,452 --> 00:31:30,374
You can only have three robes.

331
00:31:31,375 --> 00:31:37,440
The one, the under robe, the over robe, and the last two he put as one.

332
00:31:37,641 --> 00:31:38,682
You have to stitch them together.

333
00:31:39,021 --> 00:31:43,566
And that's it.

334
00:31:43,586 --> 00:31:50,972
So all these little rules that we have, these institutional rules, are there really to restrain the senses.

335
00:31:51,913 --> 00:31:52,815
That's the idea, you see.

336
00:32:01,417 --> 00:32:08,789
So it's up to you, self-restraint, like, you know, retail therapy.

337
00:32:10,772 --> 00:32:11,693
That's a bad one.

338
00:32:12,915 --> 00:32:15,019
Nipping in, getting a pair of shoes you don't really need.

339
00:32:16,561 --> 00:32:25,476
I mean, if you gave one away, if you gave one blouse away or one skirt away or one pair of trousers away and then bought another one, there might be something.

340
00:32:25,496 --> 00:32:27,679
I mean, like the wardrobes get bigger and bigger.

341
00:32:33,025 --> 00:32:34,326
Then there's non-anger.

342
00:32:34,385 --> 00:32:37,308
Oh, this is a very strange area for us.

343
00:32:38,590 --> 00:32:42,134
This question comes up often, this righteous anger.

344
00:32:43,576 --> 00:32:52,724
I mean, it's there within Christianity, depending on how you interpret the actions of Christ, you know, when he overturns the table.

345
00:32:53,967 --> 00:32:56,548
I mean, I don't see why he should necessarily have done it with anger.

346
00:32:57,810 --> 00:32:59,873
He could have done it in a dignified way, couldn't he?

347
00:32:59,893 --> 00:33:02,154
You know, just get out of here and just tip the table over.

348
00:33:02,826 --> 00:33:03,327
You know what I mean?

349
00:33:03,347 --> 00:33:06,913
Like it's, but they always think that he's all rage, like berserk.

350
00:33:08,214 --> 00:33:09,496
Which doesn't, I don't know, I don't know.

351
00:33:09,777 --> 00:33:14,063
Anyway, but this idea of righteous anger, you know.

352
00:33:15,704 --> 00:33:21,753
Anger itself, anger itself always has an underbelly of cowardice.

353
00:33:22,775 --> 00:33:25,439
Because you'll only manifest anger to somebody you can beat.

354
00:33:27,101 --> 00:33:29,964
If the person's bigger than you, you're not going to get angry.

355
00:33:32,205 --> 00:33:42,903
If the person is more powerful than you, you're going to keep it cool because you don't want to lose your job or you don't want to get flung into jail or something.

356
00:33:42,923 --> 00:33:48,712
So that anger always rests on the presumption that you'll win the battle.

357
00:33:49,653 --> 00:33:52,439
It's not a very strong position to come from, I think.

358
00:33:54,241 --> 00:33:58,028
And we have this little thing about being aggressive and being assertive.

359
00:33:58,987 --> 00:34:05,435
Now, being assertive, as far as I can see, is far more wise than being aggressive.

360
00:34:05,455 --> 00:34:08,159
And to be assertive, you don't have to be angry.

361
00:34:09,402 --> 00:34:11,123
And I think that's part of this dignity.

362
00:34:12,746 --> 00:34:14,929
It means that you're coming from the place of truthfulness.

363
00:34:19,815 --> 00:34:20,978
And the strength of that

364
00:34:25,496 --> 00:34:29,161
In, you know, today we have this problem of these wars.

365
00:34:31,184 --> 00:34:34,070
I had, just last week actually, was it last week?

366
00:34:34,090 --> 00:34:34,690
Or the week before?

367
00:34:34,971 --> 00:34:44,905
Anyway, I gave a talk to Her Majesty's Armed Forces on this business of non-violence.

368
00:34:44,925 --> 00:34:54,659
And I think the problem...

369
00:34:56,242 --> 00:35:01,271
The problem lies around this word force and violence, you see.

370
00:35:02,773 --> 00:35:05,898
I mean, force, I think, can be assertive.

371
00:35:06,860 --> 00:35:08,202
Violence is always aggressive.

372
00:35:08,242 --> 00:35:12,007
So force, so violence is force with something added.

373
00:35:12,679 --> 00:35:16,867
Violence is forced with anger, with revenge, with all that.

374
00:35:17,146 --> 00:35:30,969
Now, of course, it's difficult if you're a soldier and your mate's just got shot, not to have a sense of redress or something after the enemy.

375
00:35:30,989 --> 00:35:33,574
But I don't think it has to be like that.

376
00:35:33,594 --> 00:35:35,396
I mean...

377
00:35:35,596 --> 00:35:38,721
People who are sent out by the UN, peacekeepers.

378
00:35:38,900 --> 00:35:40,905
Even the Yiddish army does that, doesn't it?

379
00:35:40,925 --> 00:35:42,025
It was out in Israel, wasn't it?

380
00:35:43,168 --> 00:35:46,594
On the border, wasn't it?

381
00:35:46,773 --> 00:35:49,577
Their job isn't to kill, but to protect.

382
00:35:49,599 --> 00:35:52,202
It's a very different attitude, isn't it?

383
00:35:57,952 --> 00:36:01,097
So I think that distinction between force and violence is important.

384
00:36:03,456 --> 00:36:05,882
In a sense, you've got to have a righteous cause.

385
00:36:06,884 --> 00:36:10,771
That's your other problem.

386
00:36:10,791 --> 00:36:18,427
But leaving aside armed conflict, I think when we feel angry, it's this business of sublimation.

387
00:36:18,728 --> 00:36:20,351
That's another word I...

388
00:36:20,534 --> 00:36:25,199
They very rarely come across, but it's there within a lot of Christian literature in the old days.

389
00:36:25,219 --> 00:36:27,563
I just don't hear it, to sublimate.

390
00:36:27,583 --> 00:36:43,023
Now, I believe I'm right in saying, do correct me if I'm wrong, that in science, in chemistry, to sublimate means that when something sublimates, it moves from a solid directly into an air.

391
00:36:43,063 --> 00:36:44,864
What's the word I'm looking for?

392
00:36:44,885 --> 00:36:45,204
Gas.

393
00:36:45,545 --> 00:36:45,885
Thank you.

394
00:36:47,108 --> 00:36:49,731
It doesn't pass through the fluid state.

395
00:36:50,605 --> 00:36:58,557
So, somehow to, I mean anger is energy, that's all it is, it's energy.

396
00:36:59,398 --> 00:37:06,690
And to somehow turn the energy around and use it for benefit, you know, it can really give you a lot of force.

397
00:37:07,190 --> 00:37:09,534
But somehow you've got to take the turbulence out of it.

398
00:37:12,259 --> 00:37:16,005
Somehow you've got to drop down to the righteousness of your cause,

399
00:37:16,507 --> 00:37:22,016
and to work from a base of equanimity, then it becomes very powerful, I think.

400
00:37:23,039 --> 00:37:36,583
Your energy, the person's ability to stand their ground without anger has a lot more force than somebody jumping up and down.

401
00:37:38,125 --> 00:37:40,929
It's that inner strength, people feel it.

402
00:37:44,132 --> 00:37:53,268
I mean, all these people that we praise these days, like Gandhi, Martin Luther King, Nelson Mandela, all these people all have that.

403
00:37:53,929 --> 00:37:56,092
That's one thing they've really developed, isn't it?

404
00:37:57,173 --> 00:38:05,628
Not to get angry when they're being attacked, but to maintain that dignified presence and the strength that comes from it.

405
00:38:05,907 --> 00:38:06,849
It's very difficult.

406
00:38:10,913 --> 00:38:14,500
So that's this non-anger, that was non-anger.

407
00:38:19,027 --> 00:38:28,786
And then, funnily enough, they put non-violence underneath non-anger as the ninth, I think it's the ninth, is it?

408
00:38:29,289 --> 00:38:31,793
No, it's halfway down the list.

409
00:38:33,914 --> 00:38:35,878
They put non-violence, harmlessness.

410
00:38:36,117 --> 00:38:38,181
I think that's what they mean by that, harmlessness.

411
00:38:39,181 --> 00:38:46,190
So that's the positive sense is caring for all living beings, coming from a sense of care.

412
00:38:48,552 --> 00:38:52,918
Non-anger, non-violence, they're very close really, aren't they?

413
00:38:56,088 --> 00:38:59,992
And then you always get this in the list, forbearance, patience.

414
00:39:00,012 --> 00:39:03,474
The Buddha talks about it as being the greatest form of ascetic practice.

415
00:39:04,657 --> 00:39:11,242
You don't have to line the bed of nails to get the best form of ascetic practice.

416
00:39:13,125 --> 00:39:14,766
Just be patient with what you're doing.

417
00:39:14,786 --> 00:39:15,887
Enormously annoying.

418
00:39:17,909 --> 00:39:20,112
Remember old Frank Sinatra, I did it my way.

419
00:39:21,253 --> 00:39:22,134
I took the blows.

420
00:39:24,155 --> 00:39:25,217
Frank took the blows.

421
00:39:26,918 --> 00:39:47,744
and the idea that you the idea that you can't win all battles you're not going to win all your battles whether it's at work or in the family or anything somehow there has to be a point where you say well i'll give into that you know even i mean there's only myself and a manager i said itania and

422
00:39:49,108 --> 00:39:50,610
Sometimes I think, no, it's not worth it.

423
00:39:50,831 --> 00:39:51,391
Let that one go.

424
00:39:52,974 --> 00:39:57,061
And it's good practice because then you give up trying to win battles.

425
00:39:57,280 --> 00:40:02,849
You know, like, you've got to always try to be the one who gets their way.

426
00:40:03,449 --> 00:40:05,773
And just to lose a few, it's easy then, you see.

427
00:40:05,914 --> 00:40:08,356
I mean, we're not talking about immoral things.

428
00:40:09,157 --> 00:40:12,003
Just, you know, doing it my way.

429
00:40:14,646 --> 00:40:18,492
When I was a kid, I remember a raging argument between my mother and father.

430
00:40:21,239 --> 00:40:49,525
over polishing shoes my father having been in the armed forces you put the polish on with the cloth and then you brush it up with the brush bloody obvious and my mother who wasn't trained in these fine arts just used the brush all the way through the thing was the shoe came up just as bright anyway but that wasn't the point

431
00:40:52,525 --> 00:40:58,092
So it's a case of, you know, being able to sort of give in a bit sometimes.

432
00:40:59,474 --> 00:41:01,916
I think that's a quality of patience, forbearance.

433
00:41:04,139 --> 00:41:07,344
And in meditation, of course, we are, we're learning that, you see.

434
00:41:08,144 --> 00:41:11,389
You want the heart to be other than it is.

435
00:41:12,389 --> 00:41:13,652
But you can't, you have to let it go.

436
00:41:13,692 --> 00:41:21,942
If it feels a bit depressed or a bit anxious or whatever, as soon as you try to get the better of it, then you're in conflict.

437
00:41:22,900 --> 00:41:34,056
Somehow we have to be able to let the heart do its thing and yet put our energy into the way we ought to be behaving at the present time.

438
00:41:36,960 --> 00:41:38,280
And then deal with the heart later.

439
00:41:38,601 --> 00:41:43,429
You don't put yourself in conflict with your own heart, with your own mind, or with your body, heaven's sake.

440
00:41:44,230 --> 00:41:48,755
You know, like pushing the body to do things when it's not capable.

441
00:41:51,182 --> 00:42:03,536
See these, you know, when somebody comes to meditation for the first time and they have to judge, you know, from the body, but generally speaking, once you've reached 30, you know, forget the cross-leg business.

442
00:42:04,297 --> 00:42:07,900
It's just, like, it's not worth the pain.

443
00:42:07,920 --> 00:42:11,764
I mean, I did it, but I mean, looking back at that guy, it could have been easier.

444
00:42:14,168 --> 00:42:16,329
Sat there with a raging bull in your knees.

445
00:42:23,244 --> 00:42:52,829
and these little things are so annoying it's amazing how they can make us so angry about the smallest of things and that's because remember these emotions aren't caused by the object these emotions are like a big bag full of rubbish a big bag full of air, stinky air and all you got to do is put a pinprick and all of it wants to get out through there like a balloon

446
00:42:53,130 --> 00:42:59,864
So we've got all this vast reservoir of anger and self-righteousness and all that sort of stuff.

447
00:43:00,686 --> 00:43:04,394
And somebody's only got to, you know, just in the right time at the right place.

448
00:43:04,414 --> 00:43:07,059
Put a little punch in there and you go, boom!

449
00:43:07,079 --> 00:43:12,692
It's completely inappropriate.

450
00:43:13,836 --> 00:43:19,324
It's funny how we gauge when that's possible.

451
00:43:19,463 --> 00:43:28,454
If somebody comes into the house who's a stranger or a visitor, they knock something over, it's, oh, no problem.

452
00:43:28,474 --> 00:43:31,438
But if the kid does it, you go for a second.

453
00:43:31,458 --> 00:43:33,702
If the dog does it, you hang him.

454
00:43:34,119 --> 00:44:04,092
and that sort of inappropriate behaviour that we have you know just to have patience with things just develop that patience with things and then finally there's this business of uprightness and I presume that's the word for dignity really just the courage to stand up for what one thinks is right

455
00:44:06,487 --> 00:44:15,721
What's that lovely phrase, I always forget it, about, you know, if people of right mind stood up for something, then these bad things wouldn't happen.

456
00:44:16,862 --> 00:44:19,827
If they only spoke their mind and stood up for what was right.

457
00:44:21,148 --> 00:44:23,112
Have I touched upon anybody's memory?

458
00:44:24,494 --> 00:44:25,695
One of these beautiful quotes.

459
00:44:28,420 --> 00:44:31,666
Can you remember the quote?

460
00:44:32,467 --> 00:44:33,748
It's to that meaning, isn't it?

461
00:44:33,768 --> 00:44:34,570
No, no, that's about

462
00:44:36,489 --> 00:44:38,092
No, it's a different matter.

463
00:44:38,112 --> 00:44:39,233
It's a lovely thing, actually.

464
00:44:40,134 --> 00:44:44,199
For evil to flourish, it is only necessary that good men stay silent.

465
00:44:44,378 --> 00:44:44,978
That's the one.

466
00:44:44,998 --> 00:44:45,440
Sorry.

467
00:44:45,579 --> 00:44:51,425
Yes, and I want to write that down afterwards.

468
00:44:51,586 --> 00:44:52,788
Could you say that again, Ruthie?

469
00:44:53,789 --> 00:44:54,969
For evil to flourish.

470
00:44:54,989 --> 00:45:01,257
For evil to flourish, it is only necessary for good men to stay silent.

471
00:45:01,277 --> 00:45:01,637
Yeah, see?

472
00:45:01,657 --> 00:45:05,501
There may be one or two words out of place, but that is definitely what it is.

473
00:45:09,041 --> 00:45:37,530
that's it that's it you see so that's that sort of uprightness so these qualities I mean we haven't discussed other qualities that we'll I'll go into a little bit tomorrow the metta karuna the loving kindness the compassion the joy these are just things that were listed as qualities of a king who's list is that?

474
00:45:38,032 --> 00:45:43,802
Well, it comes from the Jātaka tales, it comes from later commentarial stuff.

475
00:45:45,425 --> 00:45:48,710
But it's not what the Buddha himself said?

476
00:45:48,730 --> 00:45:51,594
Not in so many words, I think, as far as I can see.

477
00:45:51,695 --> 00:45:55,320
I don't have my books, so I can't really say for absolutely sure.

478
00:45:55,340 --> 00:45:57,864
Is it presented as being from the Buddha or from his advice?

479
00:45:57,884 --> 00:46:01,349
Well, usually the Jātakas are, but they're not canonical.

480
00:46:02,592 --> 00:46:04,614
They're not put into the canon as such.

481
00:46:06,349 --> 00:46:08,351
But they'll do, won't they?

482
00:46:08,371 --> 00:46:09,913
As a list, as a sort of starter.

483
00:46:12,054 --> 00:46:28,048
It occurs to me actually, very interesting, that list is absolutely vital, given the nature of kings in those days, and in fact even today, because without a list like that, you've got mayhem, because the king is all-powerful.

484
00:46:28,449 --> 00:46:34,855
So it's a way of tempering the king's power to assign him all these qualities.

485
00:46:36,150 --> 00:46:37,213
That's right.

486
00:46:37,393 --> 00:46:46,590
In the scriptures you have this figure of the world-conquering monarch, who seems to me to be like the alter ego of the Buddha.

487
00:46:47,431 --> 00:46:54,025
So remember when he was born, the wise man said he would either be a world-conquering monarch or a fully self-enlightened being.

488
00:46:55,168 --> 00:47:08,722
And so you have this figure coming up through the scriptures of this very good, very gracious king who does everything right according to the model law and everything's very peaceful.

489
00:47:09,623 --> 00:47:14,286
And if you think about it, supposing we just took the first precept.

490
00:47:14,987 --> 00:47:20,313
Everybody on this earth took the first precept not to kill another human being.

491
00:47:20,333 --> 00:47:22,155
I mean...

492
00:47:23,958 --> 00:47:25,679
Just that, never mind the rest of it.

493
00:47:30,784 --> 00:47:35,831
It is totally revolutionary, the idea that a king shouldn't kill another human being.

494
00:47:36,130 --> 00:47:41,077
That would essentially forbid warfare, wouldn't it?

495
00:47:41,097 --> 00:47:41,536
Yeah.

496
00:47:41,556 --> 00:47:42,918
That's right.

497
00:47:42,938 --> 00:47:44,701
But by this time, he's conquered everything anyway.

498
00:47:46,862 --> 00:47:47,804
He's rolled his wheel.

499
00:47:49,204 --> 00:47:50,606
He doesn't have any opposition, really.

500
00:47:53,000 --> 00:48:21,927
there is a nice little scripture where there's lots of robbery the kingdom sort of goes into disarray because he's not kept these rules and the advice is given by the Buddha in a previous life or something is that he ought to stop inequality of payment there shouldn't be anybody who's poor

501
00:48:23,088 --> 00:48:29,579
It says when you get rid of poverty, then the stealing stops and the hatred stops and the killing will stop.

502
00:48:30,681 --> 00:48:33,244
That's an interesting ancient idea.

503
00:48:36,070 --> 00:48:37,652
So anyway, that's it.

504
00:48:37,853 --> 00:48:44,344
This gives us some ideas how we can walk around in a dignified fashion from now on.

505
00:48:46,867 --> 00:48:49,112
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

506
00:48:49,918 --> 00:48:56,503
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

